'''Cardboard Justice''' is a term conceptualised by Hope Swann, a teacher from [[De La Salle University]] in Manila, [[Philippines]]. The context of coining this term is the extrajudicial killings of criminals especially the drug peddlers in Philippines. The term is derived from a practice of some vigilante groups leaving a cardboard on the slain person with "Pusher Ako" ({{literal translation|I'm a [Drug] pusher}}) written on it.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yang|first1=Angelica Y|title=#Cardboard Justice: Are you for or against the Killings?|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/233409/cardboard-justice-are-you-for-or-against-the-killings/|website=Inquirer|accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dengate|first1=Kayla|title=The Bodies of Drug Dealers are Piling up in Philippines|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2016/08/04/the-bodies-of-drug-dealers-are-piling-up-in-the-philippines/|website=HuffingtonPost|accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> Adrienne Onday, a student from the [[University of the Philippines]] was inspired by Hope Swann which made her travel from Quezon City to [[Manila]] with a cardboard with “Lahat tayo posibleng drug pusher” ({{literal translation|All of us are possibly drug pushers}}).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Canlas|first1=KC|title=Viral: What is CardboardJustice?|url=http://www.wheninmanila.com/viral-what-is-cardboardjustice/|website=wheninmanila|accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> The movement took off in Philippines with many youngsters protesting against Cardboard Justice being carried out across the country. <ref name="Web">{{cite web|last1=Estella|first1=Gino|title=Cardboard justice Youth groups stand against killings|url=http://bulatlat.com/main/2016/08/12/cardboard-justice-youth-groups-stand-against-killings/|website=Bulatlat|publisher=Bulatlat|accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref>
