{{more citations needed|date=December 2008}} A '''legacy hero''' is a type of character, usually a [[superhero]], that is the descendant or relative of an already or previously existing hero who either inherits or adopts the name and attributes of the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/generations-the-15-best-marvel-legacy-heroes/|title=Taking Up The Mantle: The 15 Best Marvel Legacy Heroes|date=30 March 2017|publisher=|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/future-star-wars-films-focus-new-characters-not-legacy-heroes|title=Future Star Wars films to focus on new characters, not legacy heroes|first=Trent|last=Moore|publisher=|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>
One of the earliest examples of this character type was comic strip hero [[The Phantom]], assumed to be immortal by his enemies—various members of a single family, the descendants of Christopher Walker.
The term is used most often to refer to characters published by [[DC Comics|DC]] and [[Marvel comics]]. Family franchises such as DC's [[Batman]], [[Superman]], [[Wonder Woman]], [[Atom (comics)|Atom]], [[Black Canary]], [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]], [[The Flash]], [[Green Lantern]], [[Hawkman]], [[Hawkwoman]], [[The Ray]] and [[Robin (comics)|Robin]] or Marvel's [[Black Knight (comics)|Black Knight]], [[List of incarnations of Captain America|Captain America]], [[Captain Marvel (Marvel Comics)|Captain Marvel]], [[Hulk (comics)|Hulk]], [[Iron Man]], [[List of incarnations of Spider-Man|Spider-Man]], [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]], [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]], have seen several characters take up the name and abilities of the original.
In the video games series, ''[[Assassin's Creed (video game)|Assassin's Creed]],'' many of the game's characters are descended from bloodlines of Assassins.
==Legacy villain== In opposition, there have been legacy villains in fiction as well. In comics, examples are DC's [[Blockbuster (DC Comics)|Blockbuster]], [[Captain Boomerang]], and [[Clayface]]; Marvel's [[Green Goblin]], [[Mysterio]], and [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]].
One of the best examples exists in Disney's ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]'', as a multi-generational line of villains known as [[Hunter (Gargoyles)|the Hunter]], originates with the TV series' fictionalized depiction of the historic [[Gille Coemgáin of Moray]] as a boy. The young "Gillecomegain", as he is known within the series' storyline, is confronted by the evil female gargoyle [[Demona]] and slashed by her on his face,<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |year=1995 |title=Gargoyles — City of Stone (Part 1) |trans-title=|medium=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RUbuDobX484 |accessdate=April 24, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RUbuDobX484 |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |format=YouTube |time=10:10 to 10:22 |location= |publisher=Disney Shows |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref> and the trio of slash wound scars on Gillecomegain's face, carried by him for the rest of his life as he seeks his revenge on the female gargoyle, becomes part of the ''Hunter'' disguise for succeeding examples of the Demona-hunting antagonists.
