:''This article is about the Cuban taekwondo athlete. For the Puerto Rican politician, see [[Angel Matos García]].''
'''Ángel Valodia Matos Fuentes''' (born December 24, 1976 in [[Holguín]]) is a former [[Cuba]]n [[taekwondo]] athlete. He received a [[gold medal]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in [[Sydney]],<ref name=db-ol-TKD2000>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=25&sp=TKD "2000 Summer Olympics&nbsp; – Sydney, Australia&nbsp; – Taekwondo"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823081100/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=25&sp=TKD |date=2008-08-23 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on April 5, 2008)</ref> and added [[Taekwondo at the 2007 Pan American Games|another]] at the [[2007 Pan American Games]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]].

The [[World Taekwondo Federation]] banned Matos and his coach for life following an incident [[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics|at the 2008 Summer Olympics]] where Matos kicked the [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[referee]] [[Chakir Chelbat]] in the face, after being disqualified in the [[bronze medal]] match. The decision was later ratified by the [[IOC]].<ref name = "SMH_20080825">[http://www.smh.com.au/news/taekwondo/cuban-kicked-out-after-attacking-referee/2008/08/25/1219516279008.html Cuban kicked out after taekwondo disgrace] ''Sydney Morning Herald Aug 25, 2008''</ref> He was also banned for life by the same committee.

==2000 Summer Olympics==
[[Taekwondo at the 2000 Summer Olympics|At the 2000 Summer Olympics]], Matos was gold medalist in the men's middleweight (80&nbsp;kg) class.<ref name="time2004">Staff report (August 9, 2004). [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,994816,00.html The Olympians], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''</ref> In the first round, he defeated [[Felipe Soto Alvarez]] of [[Chile]] 9–2. In the quarterfinals, he defeated [[Victor Manuel Estrada Garibay]] of [[Mexico]] 2–0, besting [[Sweden|Swede]] [[Roman Livaja]] in the semifinals, 4–0. In the gold medal match Matos defeated [[Germany]]'s [[Faissal Ebnoutalib]] 3–1.<ref name="espn2000">Staff report (September 29, 2000). [http://static.espn.go.com/oly/summer00/results/taekwondo.html Summer Olympics 2000 Results - Taekwondo] ESPN.com</ref>

==2004 Summer Olympics==
Matos was the defending Olympic welterweight champion. At the [[2003 Pan American Games]], Matos was defeated 4–1 by eventual gold medalist [[Steven López]].<ref name="weir2004">Weir, Tom (August 2, 2004). [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/athens/fight/2004-08-02-lopez-cover_x.htm Lopez kicks his way to Athens with help from family], ''[[USA Today]]''</ref> He was not a medalist [[Taekwondo at the 2004 Summer Olympics|at Athens in 2004]], being ousted by Mexican Estrada 8–7, in the preliminary round of 16.

==2008 Summer Olympics==
In the bronze medal match in the men's 80+ kg class at the [[Taekwondo at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics]], Matos was set against Kazakhstan's [[Arman Chilmanov]].<ref name="guardian">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/aug/24/olympics2008.olympicstaekwondo|title=Cuban banned after assault on referee | work=The Guardian | location=London | date=2008-08-24 | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref> After he incurred a foot injury (at which point he led the match 3-2), he took a [[Kyeshi]]<ref name="guardian"/> ("suspend", medical timeout). Under [[World Taekwondo Federation]] tournament rules, players sustaining injury are allowed one minute of Kyeshi time, at the end of which the competitor in question must return to the center of the ring to resume the fight, request further time, or forfeit the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtf.org/site/rules/competition.htm#19|title=The World Taekwondo Federation}}</ref>

[[Sweden|Swedish]] referee [[Chakir Chelbat]] gave a time warning at 40 seconds, but Kyeshi elapsed without Matos returning to the center.<ref name="guardian"/> The referee ruled while he was sitting awaiting medical attention that he had taken too long during his time out and subsequently ruled he had retired.<ref name="guardian"/> "To me it was obvious he was unable to continue," his opponent [[Arman Chilmanov]] of Kazakhstan said. "His toe on his left foot was broken."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/sports/olympics/24taekwondo.html|title=Cuban athlete is barred for kicking referee’s face | work=The New York Times | date=2008-08-24 | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref> After Chilmanov was declared the winner, Matos briefly argued with Chelbat and then kicked him in the face, punched a judge in the arms, and spat on the floor of the arena before being escorted out by security with his coach, Leudis Gonzalez.<ref name="AFP/Fox">{{cite web | title = Cuban attacks judge after losing bronze in taekwondo | url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/beijing_olympics/story/0,27313,24231037-5016792,00.html | accessdate = 2008-08-23 | publisher=AFP/Fox }}</ref><ref name="ap">{{cite news|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gBc5uA2gEfcqAO50n1lqHot8aWLAD92O159G0 |title=Cuban taekwondo athlete banned after kicking ref |publisher=AP/Google |date=2008-08-23 |accessdate=2008-08-23 |first=Eric |last=Talmadge |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080825202646/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gBc5uA2gEfcqAO50n1lqHot8aWLAD92O159G0 |archivedate=August 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/taekwondo/news/newsid=251304.html |title=Kicked out: Cuban banned for life |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080824164335/http://www.nbcolympics.com/taekwondo/news/newsid%3D251304.html |archivedate=August 24, 2008 |df= }}</ref>

After the fight, Yang Jin-suk, the secretary general of the World Taekwondo Federation, apologised and said "This is an insult to the Olympic vision, an insult to the spirit of taekwondo and, in my opinion, an insult to mankind."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/23/AR2008082301905.html|title=Cuban Taekwondo Athlete Puts Worst Foot Forward|date=2008-08-24|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=2016-08-19}}</ref>

Hours later, the WTF banned Matos and González from WTF-sanctioned events for life; in a statement announcing its decision, the WTF called Matos' behaviour "a strong violation of the spirit of taekwondo and the Olympic Games."  It also deleted Matos' results from the 2008 Olympics from the records.<ref name="ap"/><ref>{{cite news |first= Ian|last= Ransom|title= Cuban banned for referee kick|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/GCA-Olympics/idUSPEK30514420080823|publisher= [[Reuters]]|date= 2008-08-23|accessdate=2008-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aSGpc2ezfJpI&refer=home|title=Cuban Taekwondo champ faces ban for kicking Olympic ref in head | work=Bloomberg | date=2008-08-23}}</ref>

Matos's coach Leudis González said of the referee's initial decision to end the fight, "He was too strict..." and accused the Kazakhstan team of offering bribes.<ref name="AFP/Fox"/> Former Cuban [[president]] [[Fidel Castro]] also defended Matos, saying he was rightfully indignant over his disqualification. "I saw when the judges blatantly stole fights from two Cuban boxers [[Boxing at the 2008 Summer Olympics|in the semifinals]]," Castro wrote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fidel Castro defends Ángel Matos' actions |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/olympics/2008/08/25/bc.cuba.castro.olympics.ap/index.html?eref=si_latest |work=CNN |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080831113340/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/olympics/2008/08/25/bc.cuba.castro.olympics.ap/index.html?eref=si_latest |archivedate=August 31, 2008 }}</ref>

